Tic, Tony Tetuila and Wizkid | Image: InformationNG Nigerian Afrobeats artiste Ayodeji Ibrahim Balogun better known as Wizkid has been slammed with a ₦30 million lawsuit over copyright infringement by music veteran Tony Tetuila. Tetuila whose real name is Anthony Olarenwaju Awotoye revealed in an Instagram post that he and Ghanaian singer Tic are suing Wizkid and DJ Tunez for violation of intellectual property: I just want to clear the air as I am hearing things coming Ghana. Yes, it is true that myself and Tic from Ghana (formerly known as Tic Tac) are both suing Wizkid and DJ Tunez at the Nigerian Federal High Court for violating our intellectual property rights from our song Fefe N’ efe. Our lawyers have advised us not to say more than that. Thank you. – Tony Tetuila”.   A post shared by Tetuila (@tonytetuilaofficial) on Dec 21, 2019 at 3:07am PST  Tetuila and Tic are suing for N30 million and are also asking for 35 percent of both the digital sales and royalties received from the song, according to court documents. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-1083353 lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525-598x598.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="1280" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525-598x598.jpg 598w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525-100x100.jpg 100w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525-200x200.jpg 200w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525-487x487.jpg 487w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525-974x974.jpg 974w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525-240x240.jpg 240w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525-480x480.jpg 480w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525-600x600.jpg 600w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131525.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> <img class="aligncenter wp-image-1083354 lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528-598x598.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="1280" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528-598x598.jpg 598w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528-100x100.jpg 100w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528-200x200.jpg 200w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528-487x487.jpg 487w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528-974x974.jpg 974w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528-240x240.jpg 240w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528-480x480.jpg 480w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528-600x600.jpg 600w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191222_131528.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> In May, DJ Tunez teamed up with Wizkid to release a track titled “Gbese”. In the song, Wizkid sang “Fefe N’efe na the beauty of a woman”.  That phrase was made popular by a 2004 song “Fefe Ne Efe” by Tic Tac featuring Tony Tetuila.  Tony Tetuila is best known for the song “My Car” which was released in 2001. He was a member of the now-defunct hip-hop group The Remedies along with Eedris Abdulkareem and Eddy Montana.